{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "For unit test generation, this entails repositioning the LLM from an autonomous generator to an intelligent assistant.",
    "The primary benefit lies in combining the speed of LLMs in generating boilerplate code and plausible test logic with the deep contextual knowledge and critical judgment of developers.",
    "Multiple user studies confirm that while LLM-generated tests may be imperfect, their high readability and the testing ideas they provide are of immense value to developers [74,108,156].",
    "Furthermore, controlled experiments have quantitatively found that developers using LLM assistance produce a significantly higher number of test cases, achieve better code coverage, and detect more bugs per unit of time compared to manual testing, albeit with the trade-off of a corresponding increase in false positive tests [114].Future opportunities lie in creating sophisticated human-machine collaborative workflows directly integrated into development environments.",
    "This moves beyond simple code completion, evolving into interactive, chat-based systems."
  ],
